  "justification": "The handleAssignment method (lines 337-394) perfectly matches the described behavior. It takes two Map parameters: activeTasks and standbyTasks (mapping TaskId to Set<TopicPartition>), and reconciles the task manager's current task ownership with new assignments. It: (1) logs the delta between existing and new assignments (lines 339-344), (2) registers subscribed topics from new active partitions via topologyMetadata.addSubscribedTopicsFromAssignment (lines 346-349), (3) prepares mutable copies of assignment maps (lines 351-352) and empty collections for recycling/closing tasks (lines 353-354), (4) locks tasks appearing in both old and new assignments (lines 356-361), (5) iterates over existing tasks via handleTasksWithoutStateUpdater/handleTasksWithStateUpdater to determine which tasks to update, recycle, or close (lines 373-384), (6) closes and recycles tasks (line 386), (7) unlocks tasks (line 388), (8) aggregates exceptions prioritizing fatal > migrated > corrupted (lines 390-391 via maybeThrowTaskExceptions), and (9) creates new tasks (line 393). This is the primary entry point for handling rebalance-triggered task assignments in Kafka Streams."
}

